A link has been posted to your Facebook feed. 12 To find out more about Facebook commenting please read the Conversation Guidelines and FAQs Trump says auto jobs 'pouring back' into U.S. Todd Spangler , Detroit Free Press Published 3:26 p.m. ET Feb. 3, 2017 | Updated 4 hours ago Blackstone CEO Stephen Schwarzman, left, and GM CEO Mary Barra, listen as President Donald Trump speaks during a meeting with business leaders in the State Dining Room of the White House in Washington, Friday, Feb. 3, 2017. (Photo: Evan Vucci, AP) 
WASHINGTON — President Donald Trump again today talked up the domestic auto industry at a meeting of American business people and others, saying he now understands regulations and other restrictions that he says have been holding the industry back. 
Seated next to General Motors CEO and Chairman Mary Barra, Trump referenced a meeting with Barra, Ford Motor Co. President and CEO Mark Fields and Fiat Chrysler CEO Sergio Marchionne last week and said he learned aspects of the auto industry he didn’t know before. 
“I learned a lot about the automobile business,” he said. “I thought I knew a lot but they are being so stymied, so restricted both with regulations and so many other reasons.” Trump & Detroit automakers
